<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06141187 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06141187 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  LOS-ANGELES; COLLEGE; FESTIVAL; VIOLENCE; VANDALISM; ROBBERY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  About 500 young revelers leaving a Mardi Gras celebration at UCLA rampagedthrough the trendy Westwood entertainment district early Sunday, smashingwindows and ransacking stores, police said.;    About 120 police officers,some mounted on horses, quelled the disturbance in 90 minutes, Lt. John Weaversaid. The looting began shortly after midnight.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UCLA MARDI GRAS PARTY TURNS TO THEFT, VIOLENCE;NINE ARRESTED  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Nine people were arrested on charges that included burglary, vandalism andbreaking curfew, Weaver said. One officer suffered a minor knee injury in afall, he said.;    At least six stores were burglarized and 17 werevandalized, police said. There was no immediate estimate of damages or lostgoods.;    It was the second wave of youth looting in Westwood this year. InMarch, a riot erupted after a theater oversold tickets to the drug-thrillerfilm, &quot;New Jack City.&quot;;    The latest incident &quot;took longer to control . . .and we had more officers out there,&quot; Weaver said.;    Weaver said the meleeoccurred as youths were leaving the annual Mardi Gras weekend festival on thecampus of the University of California, Los Angeles.;    UCLA police Sgt.Michael Shain said the festival increasingly is being tainted by too-rowdyrevelers.;    &quot;The truth of the matter is that a lot of gang members comehere,&quot; Shain said. &quot;It's not the family-oriented charity event it used to beseveral years ago.&quot;;    Extra officers were deployed to the area Sunday, butWeaver said he didn't expect a repeat of the violence.;    &quot;Sunday is a shortday for the Mardi Gras and historically has not been a problem,&quot; he said.;   Four adults were booked for investigation of burglary and another was bookedfor investigation of vandalism. Two juveniles were booked for investigation ofburglary and two others were booked for violating a 10 p.m. curfew, policesaid.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910520  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  294  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday May 20, 199100141187,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>